to open your (bleep) door, eh.

32:07.192 --> 32:08.525
Cause if this (bleep) thing
goes through

32:08.627 --> 32:11.595
everyone-everybody
for yourselves.

32:14.033 --> 32:16.199
(Ice cracking)

32:19.104 --> 32:22.673
This is one of the worst
(bleep) lakes I ever crossed.

32:22.775 --> 32:23.874
(Ice cracking)

32:25.511 --> 32:27.844
Just about off the ice, b'y.

32:29.448 --> 32:31.014
(Splashing)

32:31.116 --> 32:32.849
(Bleep), man.

32:34.019 --> 32:37.054
Hang on just in case
we (bleep) go down.

32:39.091 --> 32:40.724
30 feet...

32:42.861 --> 32:44.561
20 feet...

32:47.166 --> 32:49.333
10 feet.

32:49.435 --> 32:52.703
♪♪♪

32:52.805 --> 32:56.106
All right, we're off the ice.

32:57.576 --> 33:00.544
I can't say I'm not happy
to get off of that.

33:03.182 --> 33:05.349
I can honestly say that's one
of the worst ice crossings

33:05.451 --> 33:08.118
that I've ever crossed.

33:10.055 --> 33:12.923
Except for the time
I went through.

33:13.959 --> 33:15.425
I hope to (bleep) I can get out
of here

33:15.527 --> 33:18.295
before anything -
any of it melts any worse.

33:19.765 --> 33:22.966
<i> Narrator: As Art slogs his way</i>
<i> on to Pauingassi...</i>

33:25.204 --> 33:28.105
<i> 300 miles away</i>
<i> in northern Ontario...</i>

33:29.441 --> 33:31.441
(Engine rumbles)

33:31.543 --> 33:33.443
- I'm uh, coming up
close to Big Trout Lake.

33:35.781 --> 33:37.614
It's been a long day.

33:37.716 --> 33:39.750
I still have my load on
the back.

33:39.852 --> 33:42.786
<i> Narrator: Steph is closing</i>
<i> in on her destination,</i>

33:42.888 --> 33:47.557
<i>and still carrying her shipment</i>
<i> of building supplies.</i>

33:47.659 --> 33:51.795
- Started off the trip with
(bleep) weather,

33:51.897 --> 33:55.866
