loads shifting.

33:57.102 --> 34:00.704
<i> Narrator: 7 hours after almost</i>
<i> losing the load...</i>

34:00.806 --> 34:03.874
- Hell yeah. Finally.

34:03.976 --> 34:07.477
<i> Narrator: She arrives safely</i>
<i> at Big Trout Lake.</i>

34:07.579 --> 34:09.613
- Get 'er done.

34:09.715 --> 34:12.549
♪♪♪

34:12.651 --> 34:15.018
It's been a tough trip,
we did it.

34:15.120 --> 34:18.588
♪♪♪

34:27.900 --> 34:31.268
I'm learning there's a lot
I need to still figure out.

34:31.370 --> 34:33.303
There's a long road ahead
of me covered in ice,

34:33.405 --> 34:35.705
snow and mechanic breakdowns
and loads shifting

34:35.808 --> 34:38.041
and I'm just at the start.

34:39.278 --> 34:41.912
<i> Narrator: After tangling</i>
<i> with a shifting load</i>

34:42.014 --> 34:44.681
<i> the rookie is wiser</i>
<i> for the experience.</i>

34:44.783 --> 34:48.351
Steph: Middle of the night,
winding straps,

34:48.454 --> 34:52.622
minus (bleep) 40,
loader taking off lumber,

34:53.959 --> 34:56.226
time to sleep.

34:56.328 --> 35:00.530
♪♪♪

35:00.632 --> 35:03.033
That's all she wrote, man,
that's all she wrote.

35:06.839 --> 35:09.339
<i> Narrator: In northern</i>
<i> Manitoba...</i>

35:09.441 --> 35:10.907
(Splashing)

35:12.144 --> 35:14.344
<i> Art: I've had some pretty wild</i>
<i> experiences in my life, b'y,</i>

35:14.446 --> 35:16.680
this is one of them.

35:16.782 --> 35:19.549
<i> Narrator: After battling</i>
<i> mechanical setbacks</i>

35:19.651 --> 35:21.651
<i> and erratic weather...</i>

35:23.355 --> 35:24.955
- Well, we're going around
a big turn here,

35:25.057 --> 35:27.624
we gotta be getting' into this
little village.

35:28.794 --> 35:32.195
<i> Narrator: Art has finally</i>
<i> arrived at his destination.</i>

35:33.665 --> 35:36.433
Art: We'll stick this right
here, b'y.

35:36.535 --> 35:41.171
Well, (claps) here we are
in Pauingassi.

35:43.742 --> 35:45.075
(Door shuts)

35:45.177 --> 35:46.676
<i> Art: Yeah, the ride in was...</i>

35:46.778 --> 35:48.945
there was a couple spots
that I wasn't too keen with

35:49.047 --> 35:51.481
but hey, what are going to do,
eh?

35:52.584 --> 35:54.618
We got 'er done.
Another one under my belt

35:54.720 --> 35:56.820
now the thing is to get out
of here.

35:56.922 --> 35:58.688
And I'm gonna boot 'er back
to Winnipeg

35:58.790 --> 36:00.457
and grab another load
hopefully.

36:00.559 --> 36:02.259
So tally-ho.

36:03.996 --> 36:07.430
<i> Narrator: As Art hits</i>
<i> the trail...</i>

36:07.533 --> 36:09.900
<i> 250 miles to the east...</i>

36:11.236 --> 36:15.639
<i> another Polar delivery</i>
<i> is far from complete.</i>

36:15.741 --> 36:17.707
- Hey, team how's everybody
doing back there?

36:19.244 --> 36:21.444
Good, rolling along.

36:21.547 --> 36:23.513
(radio) How you doing, Reno?

36:23.615 --> 36:25.315
I'm doing good.

36:25.417 --> 36:27.984
(radio) Trucking along.

36:28.086 --> 36:29.686
<i> Narrator: The massive housing</i>
<i> haul</i>

36:29.788 --> 36:31.588
<i> bound for North Caribou Lake</i>

36:31.690 --> 36:35.058
<i> is putting Mark, Lisa</i>
<i> and young Reno Ward</i>

36:35.160 --> 36:38.094
<i> to the test.</i>

36:38.197 --> 36:42.232
<i> But their biggest challenge</i>
<i> is right in front of them.</i>

36:42.334 --> 36:44.501
- Okay, Lisa, we got this last
bridge here this is uh,

36:44.603 --> 36:46.903
very narrow.

36:47.005 --> 36:49.206
(radio) In fact I got everybody
in town telling us

36:49.308 --> 36:51.007
we're not gonna make it through.

36:51.109 --> 36:52.576
<i> We'll stop,</i>

36:52.678 --> 36:55.111
<i>and everybody just kind of park</i>
<i> off to the side of the road.</i>

36:59.952 --> 37:01.084
(Door shuts)

37:01.186 --> 37:03.653
Let's get a good look at it
and let's discuss,

37:03.755 --> 37:05.922
I wanna to know what you're
feeling comfortable with
on this.

37:06.024 --> 37:08.792
- Copy.
- This is no joke.

37:12.631 --> 37:14.364
Lisa: It's intimidating looking
to me.

37:14.466 --> 37:16.800
This looks so narrow.

37:20.272 --> 37:22.005
<i> Narrator: This narrow bridge</i>
<i> sits between</i>

37:22.107 --> 37:24.975
<i> two steep 18 percent grade</i>
<i> hills,</i>

37:26.411 --> 37:28.712
<i> but Lisa will only have</i>
<i> 6 inches to spare</i>

37:28.814 --> 37:30.914
<i> on either side.</i>

37:32.017 --> 37:34.150
<i> To make it up the far hill</i>

37:34.253 --> 37:38.722
<i> she'll have to thread the</i>
<i> needle at over 15 miles</i>
<i> per hour.</i>

37:38.824 --> 37:42.158
<i> Any miscalculation</i>
<i> could smoke the bridge,</i>

37:42.261 --> 37:45.795
<i> destroy the load and send Lisa</i>
<i> and her truck</i>

37:45.897 --> 37:48.331
<i> into the water.</i>

37:51.436 --> 37:53.136
Mark: You gotta be bang on here.

37:53.238 --> 37:56.473
And you gotta have speed.
We walked across the other one.

37:59.511 --> 38:00.944
Lisa: Well, the first thing
that I already see

38:01.046 --> 38:02.245
is we're into a head wind

38:02.347 --> 38:04.748
so I'm gonna have a hard time
getting a run.

38:04.850 --> 38:06.683
Reno: I think she has pretty
good markers in the middle

38:06.785 --> 38:08.685
of that bridge, those two seams.

38:08.787 --> 38:10.220
Lisa: So you think if I just
line up right

38:10.322 --> 38:13.423
with these seams
it'll just-oooh.

38:13.525 --> 38:15.925
- Wow, plus the head wind too
I mean this is--

38:16.028 --> 38:17.827
- Yeah, it's gonna be hard
to get some speed.

38:17.929 --> 38:20.163
- It's gonna move you like this.

38:21.466 --> 38:22.999
Reno: I think your definitely
best bet

38:23.101 --> 38:26.403
is to just put your steer tire
right on the edge of this

38:26.505 --> 38:29.606
and hammer down.
Lisa: Yeah.

38:29.708 --> 38:31.508
Reno: Just hit it confident
and not timid.

38:31.610 --> 38:32.942
Lisa: Copy.

38:33.045 --> 38:34.411
Mark: Don't close your eyes.

38:34.513 --> 38:36.780
Lisa: Oh darn!

38:36.882 --> 38:40.884
♪♪♪

38:40.986 --> 38:43.520
- Oh man.

38:43.622 --> 38:46.690
Looks tight. Looks tight.

38:46.792 --> 38:48.658
- Let's roll.

38:48.760 --> 38:50.026
<i> Reno: (radio) 10-4, Mark.</i>

38:50.128 --> 38:52.362
<i> Narrator: Hauling the smaller</i>
<i> payload...</i>

38:52.464 --> 38:54.197
- Ready to rock.

38:55.367 --> 38:57.033
(Engine roars)

38:57.135 --> 39:00.203
<i> Narrator: Reno will be the</i>
<i> first to brave the passage.</i>

39:00.305 --> 39:02.038
Lisa: Reno just let me know
how fast you hit it

39:02.140 --> 39:03.673
and how many gears you had
to drop.

39:03.775 --> 39:05.909
That'd be much appreciated.

39:06.011 --> 39:07.844
- Yeah, will do, Lis.

39:07.946 --> 39:09.946
Lisa: The road kind of comes
and it almost goes like this

39:10.048 --> 39:11.981
to hit the bridge
so I'm gonna have to--

39:12.084 --> 39:14.551
it's gonna be like over till
I get straight on it.

39:14.653 --> 39:16.219
I'm gonna have to go fast.

39:16.321 --> 39:18.254
Mark: (radio) I'm on the crest
here, Reno. I'm dropping down.

39:18.357 --> 39:20.123
- 10-4.

39:20.225 --> 39:29.065
♪♪♪

39:29.167 --> 39:31.568
- Oh, (bleep), here he comes.

39:32.871 --> 39:34.471
(Engine roars)

39:34.573 --> 39:37.140
<i> Mark: (radio) Good speed-good</i>
<i> speed-good speed.</i>

